t;_blank) last year, Google has faced regular eruptions from unhappy employ=
ees who wish to protest the company's politics in public. In January, a for=
mer security engineer said he had been stopped from sharing his pro-diversi=
ty views (https://www.theverge.com/2018/1/12/16882270/google-diversity-hiri=
ng-executives-cory-altheide&quot; target=3D&quot;_blank). This summer, a gr=
oup of employees successfully pressured the company to stop building an AI =
project for the military (https://www.theverge.com/2018/6/1/17418406/google=
-maven-drone-imagery-ai-contract-expire&quot; target=3D&quot;_blank). A sim=
ilar group is now pushing to prevent the company from re-entering China (ht=
tps://www.theverge.com/2018/8/16/17702464/google-search-censorship-china-pr=
otest-project-dragonfly&quot; target=3D&quot;_blank).

All of this has played out in unusually public ways =E2=80=94=C2=A0and agai=
nst a political backdrop that has grown increasingly unfriendly to Google a=
nd its parent company, Alphabet. President Trump has repeatedly tweeted bas=
eless allegations (https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/05/technology/google-tru=
mp-bias.html&quot; target=3D&quot;_blank) that the company is biased agains=
